1.1 Select Model Type

We’ll use a hyperparameter optimized random forrest: hyperparameters are inputs to our machine learning model which don’t have to do with our data, but they can affect how well our model performs. So, we’ll search for the best performing combination of hyperparameters. In this case we have two number_of_tree which controls how many trees make up our forrest and number_of_subfeatures which controls which how many of the total number of features any given decision tree can select for training. number_of_trees will range form 60 to 180 and be at 5 different values to test: 60,84,108,132,164. number_of_subfeatures will range from 1 all the way to the maximum number of avaliable features. For this first model, this range is from 1 to 329: again, the range will be split into 5 different values. This will result in 25 random forest models being trained with the best performing model being selected as the winner.

1.2 Build the model with all variables

allAccPlot, allQQPlot, allPiPlot, allMach = modelPredictions(df,targetVar," ","all",modelType,test,train)
import MLJDecisionTreeInterface ✔

1.2.1 Model Accuracy

The \(x\)-coordinate of this plot is the actual measured value of the \(\text{CO}_2\); the \(y\)-coordinate is the predicted value for \(\text{CO}_2\). Training data is ploted in blue and testing/validation data in red.

We can see that the testing \(R^2\) is great. Additionally, the RMSE is fairly low when compared the to total range of the measured \(\text{CO}_2\). This indicates that our model generalized quite well. There is a gap in the measurements between 700 and 800 ppm which will no doubt cause some issue in predictive capability of the model.

Code 
allAccPlot

1.2.2 Quantile-Quantile Plot

A quantile-quantile plot shows the difference between between the distributions of two quantities: in this case, it is the difference between the distribution of the actual (\(x\)-axis) and predicted \(\text{CO}_2\) values (\(y\)-axis). This is another way to check that the model generalized well because if the model can produce the same probability distributions, then it has learned to capture the behavior that the data displays.

As expected, the distributions don’t match up quite well in the 700 to 800 ppm range; however outside of this range, the data fits rather well to the 1:1 line.

Code 
allQQPlot

1.2.3 Permutation Importancs

The permutation importance measures the effect a variable has on the performance of a trained model. It is therefore a wrapper based method. We can see that there is a sharp drop off in the importance from ECG to FT10-beta. Furthermore, there are additional sharp drop offs in importance. This is a classic sign that there are too many input features e.g “too many cooks in the kitchen”. So, despite having a very accurate model, it isn’t simple (there are 329 features afterall.) Let’s see if we can’t reduce the number of features.

Code 
allPiPlot

2 Apply BARS

3 Feature Selection Time!

The idea here is that we have a wrapper and filter method - PI importance and BARS - which we can use to select the top performing features. The model gives us some insight into the best features, but this insight depends on the explicit assumptions of the model. The filter method uses a different set of criteria to judge whether or not a feature is good to use. Hitting feature selection from both angles of attack generates a more robust set of model variables. Here we plot PI vs BARS. The method we use to select the best features is to independently rank variables by their PI and their BARS, calculate the quantiles for each ranking method, and finally choose a thresholding value (95th quantile) that a feature must either meet or exceed to be chosen as a feature for the BARS model.

Code

3.1 Combining Wrapper and Filter Methods

The plot below shows - in the green shaded region - the variables that are in the top 5% of variables as scored by both BARS (filter method) and permutation importance (wrapper method). Recall that filter methods do not require the construction of a predictive model from all of the data before applying them. By combining both wrapper and filter methods, we get a more robust feature selection process.

Code 
n = 100
threshold = 95
FSplot=scatter(piscores,
          unsortedBars,
          xlabel = "Permutation Importance",
          ylabel = "BARS",
          label=false,
          legend = :outertopright,
          title = "Feature Selection")
barsQuantiles = ntiles(sortedBars,n)
piQuantiles = ntiles(sortedpiscores,n)
vline!([piQuantiles[n-threshold] for i∈1:length(piQuantiles)],linecolor=:gold, label = false)
hline!([barsQuantiles[n-threshold] for i∈1:length(barsQuantiles)],linecolor=:gold, label = "$(threshold)% Quantile")
selectedFeatures=[]
for i∈1:length(unsortedBars)
    if unsortedBars[i]≥barsQuantiles[n-threshold] && piscores[i]≥piQuantiles[n-threshold]
        push!(selectedFeatures,FSdataframe.Feature_Name[i])
    end
end

best_xlims = (piQuantiles[n-threshold],maximum(piscores))
best_ylims = (barsQuantiles[n-threshold], maximum(unsortedBars))
plot!([piQuantiles[n-threshold],maximum(piscores)],
      [barsQuantiles[n-threshold],maximum(unsortedBars)],
      fillrange = best_ylims,
      fillalpha = 0.2,
      fillcolor = :green,
      linealpha = 0.0,
      label = "best variables"
      )

initVertPos = .8*findmax(unsortedBars)[1]
horzPos = 1.3*findmax(piscores)[1]
i=.075*initVertPos
annotate!([horzPos],[initVertPos],text("Variables: ",:black,:center,8))

for entry∈selectedFeatures
    annotate!([horzPos],[initVertPos-i],text(entry,:red,:center,6))
    i+=.075*initVertPos
end
